During this internship, I had the opportunity to work on a project that leveraged advanced machine learning techniques to classify medical images. Specifically, I developed and trained convolutional neural network (CNN) models to distinguish between MRI images of tuberculosis, COVID-19, and healthy kidneys.

In addition to implementing the CNN models, I also created a web application with a user-friendly interface for doctors to use in their decision-making processes. The front-end of the application was built with ReactJS, while the back-end utilized the Flask Python framework to deploy and load the models via API.

Overall, this project allowed me to gain hands-on experience with a variety of cutting-edge technologies and apply them to a real-world scenario. It was a challenging but rewarding experience that further solidified my passion for computer science and the impact it can have on healthcare.

description:
As a 10 years young boy my father offered me a small RC car.I spent days enjoying this new toy but multiple questions were popping inside my head. There is no wire between the car and the controller,  why does it move when I push the buttons? What makes it follow my order correctly to turn left or right? I was curious to understand what was happening inside. A few days later I decided to unscrew it. I was fascinated by the process and discovering the different parts, the engine, the damper and the circuitry.the most intriguing part was a green piece of plastic which my father told me it is the PCB, where all the program is stored to handle the actions between the car and what I want it to execute. That was the moment when a spark light in my brain, the passion to know more about what is a program? how to make it and how to put it in the work ? My beautiful car was lost. I was unable to assemble it back, some parts were broken but I learned a great lesson and a new passion.
This passion carried me through the years of my education to grasp advanced topics like programming, computer science, mathematics, and machine learning. For me every course was interesting to learn if it is a step to build highly automated pieces of software which point me toward machine learning and the importance of data which contain human expertise that can be intuitively injected into algorithms to mimic various types of  patterns.
Now as a senior data scientist I’m lucky to say that my daily job is also my passion. I was able to put in practice those accumulated skills to leverage business challenges and help shape the strategic decision of the company.

jobDescription2:
Subject: Optimal control applied to bacterial growth under the supervision of Mr. Jean-Baptiste Caillau (Université Côte d'Azur, CNRS, Inria, LJAD) 

Recent work [1] indicates that bacterial growth is realistically represented by so-called "self-replicator" models. These dynamic models in which the allocation of resources reflects the "choices" made by the bacteria between different internal mechanisms allow the use of an optimal control approach to describe its behaviour. Several criteria are then possible: maximization of growth, maximization of the production of a product of interest... We are interested in the numerical resolution of this type of problem by direct or indirect approaches in the Julia language.

 [1] Yabo, A. G.; Caillau, J.-B.; Gouzé, J. L.; de Jong, H.; Mairet, F. Dynamical analysis and optimization of a generalized resource allocation model of microbial growth. SIAM J. Appl. Dyn. Syst. 21 (2022), no. 1, 137-165
